The Herald Kudakwashe Mugari in Maputo, Mozambique PRESIDENT Mnangagwa has kick-started his three-day State visit to the Republic of Mozambique with a meeting with his counterpart President Filipe Nyusi. <img class="size-full wp-image-609939" src="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2022/04/WhatsApp-Image-2022-04-04-at-10.51.59-AM.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2022/04/WhatsApp-Image-2022-04-04-at-10.51.59-AM.jpg 680w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2022/04/WhatsApp-Image-2022-04-04-at-10.51.59-AM-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> President Mnangagwa and Felippe Nyusi inspecting a guard of honour. The President, who was received with a 21-gun salute, also inspected a guard of honour. <img class="size-full wp-image-609936 aligncenter" src="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2022/04/WhatsApp-Image-2022-04-04-at-10.51.58-AM-1.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2022/04/WhatsApp-Image-2022-04-04-at-10.51.58-AM-1.jpg 680w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2022/04/WhatsApp-Image-2022-04-04-at-10.51.58-AM-1-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" />
The meeting is taking place exactly two months after President Mnangagwa’s one –day official working visit here in Beira where the two leaders agreed to facilitate the emancipation of their people through economic development.